What is Linux?
Linux is an open-source operating system used to run computers, servers, mobiles, cloud systems, and embedded devices.

-> Created by Linus Torvalds (1991)
-> Based on UNIX
-> Source code is free and customizable
-> Very popular in servers, cloud, DevOps, and cybersecurity

Examples of Linux Distributions (Distros):
-> Ubuntu
-> CentOS
-> Red Hat (RHEL)
-> Debian
-> Kali Linux
-> Amazon Linux

Where Linux is used:
-> Web servers (Google, Facebook, Amazon)
-> Cloud platforms (AWS, Azure, GCP)
-> DevOps tools & CI/CD
-> Supercomputers
-> Android phones (Android is Linux-based)

Linux vs. Windows
-------------------Linux-------vs---------------Windows
Type:	             Open-source------------------Closed-source
Cost:              Free-------------------------Paid license
Customization:	   Highly customizable----------Limited
Security:	         Very secure------------------More virus-prone
Performance:	     Fast & lightweight-----------Heavier
Updates:	         User-controlled--------------Forced updates
CLI Support:	     Very powerful----------------Limited (improving)
Server usage:	     Very high--------------------Less


GUI vs CLI Comparison

	               GUI-----vs-------CLI
Speed:	         Slow-------------Fast
Memory usage:    High-------------Low
Automation:	     Difficult--------Easy
Server usage:	   Rare-------------Mostly
DevOps use:   	 Less-------------More

Why DevOps Engineers Mostly Use Linux?
DevOps engineers mostly use Linux because production servers, cloud platforms, and DevOps tools are Linux-based, and Linux provides powerful CLI, automation, security, and stability.





